04961nam a22005655i 9780228003137DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280031377 a10.1515/97802280031372doi  a(DE-B1597)656552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0620002bisacsh04a320.1/222300aGeopolitical Amnesia :bThe Rise of the Right and the Crisis of Liberal Memory /ced. by Vibeke Schou Tjalve. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAnglo-American Amnesia -- tAfter Empire: The ‘Geopolitical Mind’ of the Anglo-American Right -- tAfter Liberalism? The Paleoconservative Roots of the New American Nationalism -- t‘A Test of Character’: The Positive Psychology of War -- tCONTINENTAL MEMORY WARS -- tPost-Liberal Visions: Memory, Virility, and Geopolitics on the French New Right -- tWhat Liberalism? Russia’s Conservative Turn and the Liberal Order -- tGerman Memory Culture between the Right and the Mainstream -- t‘The Long Night of the Second Republic‘1: Geopolitical Amnesia in Italy -- tThe New Geopolitics? -- tThe Forgotten Pragmatism of the United Nations: A Halfway House between Nationalism and Cosmopolitanism -- tThe New Geopolitics: Towards a More Virulent World? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFar-right movements, parties, and governments are changing the language and logic of international order. Zero-sum geopolitics - from Donald Trump to Brexit - and the rhetoric of putting the national interest "first" are back, and along with them come a deep fascination with the values of patriarchy, masculinity, and strength. Putting these dramatic shifts in contemporary American and European foreign policy into wider historical and intellectual context, Geopolitical Amnesia explores the liberal crisis beneath the resurgence of far-right ideas. Drawing on memory studies, it addresses the ways in which the new geopolitics intersects and interplays with an exhausted and amnesiatic liberalism. Scholars with expertise on national and regional ideological traditions look at contemporary memory wars - competing revisionist histories - from Washington to Warsaw, and from the Anglosphere to Southern, Western, and Eastern Europe. They address the changing conditions of memory and nostalgia and discuss how and why it matters that the new geopolitics takes place in an age of accelerated, fragmented, and digitalized global media. Timely and ambitious, this accessible collection reveals the far-right ideas behind the return of geopolitics and the crisis of liberalism that paved its way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Geopolitics.2bisacsh1 aAndersen, Louise Riis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrone, Manni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrolet, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsborg, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinds, Matthew Fallon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolm, Minda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTassinari, Fabrizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTjalve, Vibeke Schou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTjalve, Vibeke Schou, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary